*On the Bus

*Small Class-Sizes (1:14 Teacher to Student Ratio)
*Block Schedule for more instructional time.
*Online-Teacher Direct Instruction for Remote Learning Days.
*6 Ft Social Distancing provided in each classroom.
*Full-time school nurse
*Limited Transitions and Cohort Groupings
*No Uniform
*Free Breakfast and Lunch
*School Supplies Provided

Call 317-423-0204 or Find us on Enroll Indy.

Good afternoon SENSE families- I am excited to announce that as of today, SENSE Charter School will open for the 2020-2021 school year on July 27th. While I am still awaiting final guidance from the Marion County Health Department, we have worked diligently over the past several months to develop a plan that promotes both in person and on-line learning opportunities (computers and hotspots being provided to those who need them) while promoting social distancing and appropriate screeners to help prevent sickness. It is my hope that on or before July 6th, a complete plan for re-entry can be shared. I look forward to seeing you all very soon!
Dr. Kristie Sweeney:

THIS IS OPEN TO ALL STUDENTS UNDER THE AGE OF 18 REGARDLESS OF WHAT SCHOOL YOU ATTEND!

The IPS Food Service team will distribute pre-packaged meals from the parking lot at seven IPS schools.

Meals will be distributed between 11 a.m. to 1 p.m. Monday–Friday from the following locations:

George Washington High School, 2215 W. Washington St.
Arlington Woods School 99, 5801 30th St.
Brookside School 54, 3150 E. 10th St. (Meals will be served from the school parking lot off of North Dearborn Street.)
Carl Wilde School 79, 5002 W. 34th St. (Meals will be served from the parking lot off of Auburn Road.)
Eleanor Skillen School 34, 1410 Wade St.
James Whitcomb Riley School 43, 150 W. 40th St.
Charles Warren Fairbanks School 105, 8620 Montery Road
Meal service is open to all students age 18 and younger, including non-IPS students. Meals are available on a first-come, first-served basis.

post_text: Thanks to all who put the FUN in our SENSE Charter Winter Festival. Under the coordination of 7th and 8th grade social studies teacher, Mr. Hedges, our 8th grade students created and ran the many amazing activities and games for the event. Everyone had a great time playing the games, winning prizes and transforming themselves at the face painting station. We raised close to $600, which will be used to fund school field trips. Pictured here is one of our families who attended the event. They are smiling because they had fun, won many prizes, including a doll house! Thanks to all those who came out and supported our event.
